<DOC><DOCNO> AP890907-0222 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-89 1515EDT</FILEID><FIRST>s i BC-Peru-Note Adv10   09-07 0147</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Peru-Note, Adv 10,0148</SECOND><HEAD>$Adv10</HEAD><HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 10 or Thereafter</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: For use with BC-Peru-Cocaine War, b0586; and BC-Peru-Rebel Justice,b0587.</HEAD><NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE><TEXT>   A 150-mile-long valley in central Peru is theworld's biggest producer of the coca leaf used in making cocaine anda main supplier of the drug cartels of neighboring Colombia. MonteHayes, AP bureau chief in Lima, recently visited two key areas ofthe Upper Huallaga River Valley _ one, a government base from whichthe United States will soon be going to war against the cocainetrade at its source, an possibly against anti-government Maoistguerrillas; the other, a stronghold of the guerrillas who arecooperating with drug traffickers but also lay down tough laws oftheir own in the villages they control, including a ban on drugabuse. Here are his reports.</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv Sunday, Sept. 10</NOTE></DOC>